# Python conventions

## Baseline

- Target the latest stable Python the repo supports; declare in `pyproject.toml`.
- PEP 8 enforced by `ruff format` + `ruff check`.
- Type hints on all public functions; strict `mypy` / `pyright` in CI.
- Prefer standard library; add third-party only with clear justification.

## Style

- Functions do one thing; extract helpers before nesting more than two levels.
- Composition over inheritance; protocols (`typing.Protocol`) for structural typing.
- Dataclasses / Pydantic for data containers; no ad-hoc dicts for typed payloads.
- F-strings for formatting; avoid `%` and `.format` except in legacy code.

## Typing

- `any` only as a last resort; prefer `object`, generics, or a proper protocol.
- `Optional[X]` via `X | None`.
- `Literal`, `TypedDict`, and discriminated unions for precise domain modelling.
- Return-type annotations are mandatory on public callables.

## Async

- `async def` for I/O-bound concurrency.
- Never block the event loop (no `time.sleep`, no CPU-heavy work) â€” offload via `asyncio.to_thread` or a process pool.
- Use `asyncio.TaskGroup` (3.11+) for structured concurrency.
- Timeouts on every external call (`asyncio.timeout(...)`).

## Errors

- Custom exception classes for domain errors; inherit from a package base.
- Never catch bare `Exception` unless you re-raise or log+raise.
- No exception-for-flow-control; use return values or sentinels.

## Testing (pytest)

- Tests live next to code (`tests/` or `_test.py`) and cover happy path + edge cases + error paths.
- Parametrise with `@pytest.mark.parametrize` rather than copy-pasted bodies.
- Use fixtures for shared setup; keep them narrow.
- Coverage target â‰Ą 85% on non-trivial modules; meaningful branches, not padding.

## Tooling

- `ruff` for lint + format (replaces flake8/black/isort).
- `mypy --strict` or `pyright strict`.
- `uv` or `pip-tools` for dependency resolution; lockfile committed.
- `pre-commit` with ruff + mypy + tests on changed files.

## Performance

- Profile with `cProfile` / `py-spy` before optimising.
- Use generators / iterators for large sequences.
- Vectorise with NumPy/Polars where appropriate; avoid Python-level loops on large arrays.

## Output format when writing code

- Application code and tests in separate blocks.
- Include `pyproject.toml` / requirements snippet when external deps are introduced.
- Call out any assumption made about Python version or environment.
